## Meta Descriptions: Your Free Google Ad Copy

Meta descriptions don’t directly affect rankings—Google has confirmed this. But they _massively_ affect whether someone clicks your result over the next one. And click-through rate **does** influence rankings over time.

Your meta description is 150-160 characters of persuasion. It needs to do three things:

1.  **Confirm relevance.** Echo the search intent so the user knows your page answers their question.
2.  **Differentiate.** Why should they click _your_ result instead of the other nine on the page?
3.  **Include a call to action.** “Book online,” “See pricing,” “Learn more”—tell them what to do next.

Here’s a real example from a practice I worked with. Their Botox page had no meta description, so Google auto-generated one from their navigation menu: _“Home | About | Services | Contact | Blog.”_ We replaced it with: “Get natural-looking Botox results from board-certified injectors in \[City\]. See before/after photos and book your consultation today.” Click-through rate went from 1.8% to 4.6%.

That’s the same ranking position, more than **double the clicks**. More clicks, more patients, zero additional ad spend. If you’re investing in [Google Ads](https://regtekconsulting.com/google-ads/) alongside organic, your descriptions should work just as hard as your paid ad copy.

